{"type":"message","id":"b3f290f0","parentId":"3ad67eef","timestamp":"2026-05-12T12:23:50.093Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue clearly. The `logging.basicConfig` in the script does NOT use `encoding='utf-8'`. On Windows with Big5/cp950, this causes garbled Chinese characters. But actually, the log output shows `delisted` errors, so the issue must be somewhere else.\n\nWait, looking at the log output again - it shows ERROR messages. But I checked the script and there's no explicit `logging.error()` call. The ERROR messages must be coming from yfinance itself. When yfinance fails, it prints to stdout/stderr.\n\nBut the log shows:\n```\n2026-05-12 14:47:03,188 [ERROR] \n1 Failed download:\n\n\n2026-05-12 14:47:03,188 [ERROR] ['EX443']: possibly delisted; no timezone found\n```\n\nThese are yfinance's own error messages. So the problem is that yfinance is generating these ERROR logs directly, not the Python script itself. I need to figure out how to suppress or redirect yfinance's stderr output.\n","thinkingSignature":"8e2b142b2f8ac2ffdc968e196fcfa75fea9427128957ba1ac9988fc9c0830470"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_s21iftoaauhr_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"\nimport re\nc = open(r'C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\agents\\ray\\ray_backtest_630.py', encoding='utf-8', errors='ignore').read()\n# Find all logging calls\nlog_matches = [(m.start(), c[max(0,m.start()-30):m.start()+100]) for m in re.finditer(r'_log\\.|logging\\.|print\\(', c)]\nprint(f'Total logging/print calls: {len(log_matches)}')\nfor p, s in log_matches[:10]:\n    print(f'  ...{s[:80]}...')\n\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":63,"output":383,"cacheRead":127744,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128190,"cost":{"input":0.0000189,"output":0.0004596,"cacheRead":0.0076646399999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00814314}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":177858861