{"type":"message","id":"45855b3f","parentId":"757ed710","timestamp":"2026-05-12T12:24:14.236Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All loggers seem to already have `encoding='utf-8'`. But the logs show garbled Chinese. This means the encoding issue might be:1. The log was written BEFORE the encoding was set (different session)\n2. The problem is with `sys.stdout.reconfigure(encoding='utf-8')` - this only affects print(), not logging\n\nWait - the log file shows `?` characters. This could be:\n1. Windows console encoding issue (the original writes went through a console with cp950)\n2. The FileHandler IS set to utf-8 but the stream was opened before\n\nActually wait - looking at the logs again, the garbled characters appear on lines where the timestamp + \"[INFO]\" are followed by Chinese that appears as `?`. \n\nThe logging.basicConfig in ray_backtest_630.py uses `basicConfig` without explicit encoding. `basicConfig` creates a FileHandler without specifying encoding, so it defaults to the system encoding (cp950 on Chinese Windows). That's the issue.\n\nFor the other files, they use `FileHandler` with explicit `encoding='utf-8'`, but the garbled text still appears. The garbled content was from the ray_data_center.log - maybe it was written by an older version of the script before the encoding was added.\n\nLet me focus on what I can confirm and fix:\n\n1. **ray_backtest_630.py**: `basicConfig` doesn't specify encoding → fix to use `encoding='utf-8'`\n2. **The 97KB flood**: The logging actually goes to FileHandler (from basicConfig) but yfinance errors were being printed to stdout, not logged. The 97KB comes from console output + stderr mixed together.\n3. **feedparser**: Need to install it or redirect to Tavily\n4. **Jina Reader 403**: Replace with Tavily or MiniMax web\n\nLet me now execute the actual fixes.\n","thinkingSignature":"6d1f4430328de263f05f6c97795184c006ca5e981a398ed87dc62af9dbcb10e1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fun