{"type":"message","id":"529cdd90","parentId":"f9436a4c","timestamp":"2026-05-12T12:25:20.514Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ERROR logs aren't coming from `ray_backtest_630.py` itself. They're coming from yfinance internally when called from another script. Let me look at what the actual `ray_backtest_630f.py` or another related script does. But since the log file is `ray_backtest_630.log` and the script is `ray_backtest_630.py`, the ERROR messages must come from yfinance's internal logging being routed to that file via `basicConfig`.\n\n`logging.basicConfig` applies globally to the root logger. So any `logging.error()` anywhere in the Python process will go to that file. The yfinance library internally logs ERROR messages when downloads fail. So when `ray_data_center.py` (or another script that imports this log config) downloads symbols and fails, the ERROR goes to `ray_backtest_630.log`.\n \nLooking at the actual log entries, the yfinance errors are being written to the file, but I'm not seeing where the script itself is logging those skipped symbols. The `else: skipped += 1` block suggests the script tracks skipped symbols, but I need to find if there's a corresponding `_log.info()` call that would output the completion message.\n\nWait, I think I see the issue now. The `ray_backtest_630.py` script's `backtest_symbol` function has no exception handling at all—it just returns `None` on any failure. But the log file shows ERROR messages from yfinance, which means these are coming from somewhere else. When I look at `ray_data_center.py`, I can see it has a `FileHandler` configured for `ray_data_center.log`, so the yfinance errors must be getting logged there instead, or there's another script that's actually calling yfinance and handling exceptions differently. So the root logger is writing to `ray_backtest_630.log`, and when yfinance raises those delisted errors, they're being captured there instead of going to the individual log file. The solution is to disable the yfinance logger in `ray_backtest_630.py` so those ERROR messages don't flood the log, and switch to using `DEBUG` level for suppression instead. Let me start applying these fixes.\n","thinkingSignature":"27767de235a4d2ef050bae8bf5b5c0cd30c0ae4c283f2940b5622b655c91267f"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_c773tmdhnpm5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"\nimport re\nc = open(r'C:\\Users\\USER\\.openclaw\\agents\\ray\\ray_backtest_630.py', encoding='utf-8', errors='ignore').read()\n# Find ALL error-related logging\nlog_calls = re.findall(r'logging\\.\\w+\\([^)]+\\)|_log\\.\\w+\\([^)]+\\)', c)\nprint('All logging calls:')\nfor lc in log_calls:\n    print(f'  {lc}')\nprint()\nprint('All logging.getLogger calls:')\nloggers = re.findall(r'logging\\.getLogger\\([^\\)]+\\)', c)\nfor l in loggers:\n    print(f'  {l}')\n\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":297,"output":625,"cacheRead":129536,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":130458,"cost":{"input":0.0000891,"output":0.00075,"cacheRead":0.007772159999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.008611259999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778588705081,"responseId":"06524f236a8cc4c6bea39e11b6681674"}}
