{"type":"message","id":"311de1e2","parentId":"0c11b6bc","timestamp":"2026-05-12T12:25:37.724Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting. The `ray_backtest_630.py` only has `_log.info()` calls (INFO level) in the log file. So the ERROR lines in the log don't come from `ray_backtest_630.py` directly.\n\nBut the log shows `[ERROR]` - which would only appear if something logs with level ERROR. But `logging.basicConfig` was set with `level=logging.INFO` so it wouldn't show ERROR level from this script's logger.\n\nWait - maybe the script itself uses `logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)` which applies to ALL loggers including yfinance's logger? That means yfinance's ERROR messages (which are logged at ERROR level by yfinance) would be captured because:\n1. `basicConfig` sets the root logger level to INFO (so it won't capture ERROR from root - wait, no. If level=INFO, it means INFO and above (WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL) are captured. So ERROR would be captured.\n\n\n2. The yfinance library is likely the culprit - it's probably logging those delisted warnings at ERROR level, and since the root logger is configured with `level=logging.INFO` via basicConfig, those messages get captured in the log file even though they're not coming from `ray_backtest_630.py` itself.\n\nThe solution would be to set the yfinance logger to a higher threshold like WARNING or CRITICAL so it stops propagating those noisy messages, or disable yfinance's logger entirely.\n","thinkingSignature":"223bb69ba87699ee8b9d7932d4aab0cf6823a0efdd23d0afdfb88132ad02447d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2la6610a74dx_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"\nimport logging\n# Get yfinance logger\nyh_logger = logging.getLogger('yfinance')\nprint('yfinance level:', yh_logger.level)\nprint('yfinance handlers:', yh_logger.handlers)\nprint('yfinance propagate:', yh_logger.propagate)\n\n# Check root logger\nroot = logging.getLogger()\nprint('Root level:',